data.title: Bryan Cranston wins best leading actor award at Tony Awards for All the Way
data.meta_description: Posing up with old Breaking Bad co-star Anna Gunn seemed to be a good luck charm for Byran Cranston, as he went on to win the coveted Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Play gong at the Tony Awards on Sunday
data.text:
His good luck charm! Bryan Cranston reunites with Breaking Bad co-star Anna Gunn at The Tonys... and goes on to win Best Leading Actor gong

It was one of the few awards to have eluded him.

But posing with old Breaking Bad co-star Anna Gunn seemed to be a good luck charm for Byran Craston, as he went on to win the coveted Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Play gong at the Tony Awards on Sunday.

He grinned with glee as he stood with his former on-screen wife as he mingled with fellow luvvies on the pre-show red carpet.

Scroll down for video

And he was smiling even more when it was announced he had added yet another expensive paperweight to his full-to-bursting trophy cabinet.

Bradley Cooper presented the gong to the delighted actor.

Bryan won for a role far removed from his chemistry teacher-turned-meth mogul Walter White, and was recognised for his turn as former President Lyndon B. Johnson in Robert Schenkkan's All the Way, which was, amazingly, his Broadway debut.

The talented 58-year-old beat off Twelfth Night's Samuel Barnett, Of Mice And Men's Chris O'Dowd, Richard III's Mark Rylance and Act One'sTony Shalhoub to win the prize.

And his former co-star Aaron Paul shared a screengrab taken from his TV of Bryan winning and posted it to Instagram with the message: 'Congratulations to my dear friend and mentor of mine Bryan Cranston on his brand new Tony Award. So happy for you brother.'

The versatile star had already won many awards for his film and television work, winning three Emmys and a Golden Globe for his turn in Breaking Bad alone.

His comedy chops were also praised during his spell as the titular character's father in sitcom Malcolm In The Middle.

While he had a great time chatting to Anna, 45, who played long-suffering Skyler White from 2008 to 2013, Bryan had his real life leading lady on his arm on Sunday.

For he walked down the red carpet with his wife Robin Dearden, whom he met when they both appeared in an episode of Airwolf back in 1984.
